SIMPLE: manuscript
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Manuscript
<hw>Man"u*script</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>manu
scriptus</ets>. See <er>Manual</er>, and <er>Scribe</er>.]</ety>
<def>Written with or by the hand; not printed; <as>as, a
<ex>manuscript</ex> volume</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manuscript</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Manuscript
<hw>Man"u*script</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[LL. <ets>manuscriptum</ets>,
lit., something written with the hand. See <er>Manuscript</er>,
<pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An original literary or musical
composition written by the author, formerly with the hand, now usually
by typewriter or word processor. It is contrasted with a printed
copy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Writing, as opposed to print; <as>as, the book
exists only in <ex>manuscript</ex></as>.</def>
<rj><au>Craik.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The word is often abbreviated to <abbr>MS.</abbr>,
plural <abbr>MSS.</abbr></note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Manuscriptal</ent>⟦br⟧
